[[simple:Tagata Shrine]] [[sn:Tagata Shrine]] [[en:Tagata Shrine]] [[ja:田縣神社]] [[Category:Buildings and structures in Komaki]] [[Category:History of Komaki]] [[Category:Shikinaisha in Owari Province]] [[Category:Human gender and sexuality symbols]] [[Category:Former Gō-sha in Aichi Prefecture]] [[Category:Shinto shrines in Aichi Prefecture]] [[Category:Sexuality in Shinto]] [[Category:translated pages with valid en interwikis]] <!--jawiki derived wikidata interwikis--> {{Commons category|Tagata Shrine}} [[fr:Tagata-jinja]] [[min:Kuil Tagata]] [[zh:田縣神社]] <!--enwiki derived wikidata interwikis--> {{Commons category|Tagata Shrine}} [[fr:Tagata-jinja]] [[min:Kuil Tagata]] [[zh:田縣神社]] [[Category:qq]]

{{afc comment|Wikidata entry [[d:Q60581]] Wikidata name: Tagata Shrine [[User:Immanuelle|Immanuelle]] ([[User talk:Immanuelle|talk]]) 09:41, 11 June 2025 (UTC)}} {{Short description|Shinto shrine}}
{{Infobox religious building| religious_affiliation = [[Shinto]]|religious_affiliation = [[Shinto]]|religious_affiliation = [[Shinto]]|religious_affiliation = [[Shinto]]| religious_affiliation = [[Shinto]] | religious_affiliation = Shinto | religious_affiliation = [[Shinto]] |image = File:Tagata jinja haiden 2020-12 ac (1).jpg | deity = {{ill|Toshigami|qid=Q3028663}} | location = {{ill|Komaki|qid=Q389537}} | coordinates = {{Coord|35.31583333|N|136.94111111|E|region:JP_type:landmark|display=inline,title}} }} '''Tagata Shrine''' (田縣神社) is a small shrine located in [[:en:Komaki|Komaki]] City, [[:en:Aichi Prefecture|Aichi Prefecture]], Japan, near [[Nagoya Airfield]].<ref name="Picken-2010">{{Cite book |last=Picken |first=Stuart D. B. |url=https://www.amazon.ca/Historical-Dictionary-Dictionaries-Religions-Philosophies-ebook/dp/B004MYFMR6/ref=sr_1_1?keywords=9780810873728&linkCode=qs&qid=1700275947&s=books&sr=1-1 |title=Historical Dictionary of Shinto |date=2010-12-28 |publisher=Scarecrow Press |edition=2 |language=English}}</ref>{{Rp|page=6}}
Tagata Shrine is famous for its Harvest Festival [[Hōnensai]], or the penis festival held annually on March 15.<ref name="e-periodica" /><ref name="Knapp-1997">{{Cite book |last=Knapp |first=Bettina L. |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5isFdtMGwVwC&dq=tagata+shrine&pg=PA246 |title=Women in Myth |date=1997-01-01 |publisher=SUNY Press |isbn=978-0-7914-3164-1 |language=en}}</ref> The festival has received large amounts of attention.<ref name="e-periodica">https://www.e-periodica.ch/cntmng?pid=act-001%3A1959%3A16%3A%3A995</ref>
It is near [[Ōagata Shrine]] which has a similar yonic festival the Sunday before this festival.<ref name="D-2012">{{Cite web |last=D |first=John |date=2012-03-24 |title=Fertility festival (Oh-agata/ Oagata Jinja) |url=https://www.greenshinto.com/2012/03/24/hime-no-miya-festival-ogata-jinja/ |access-date=2023-04-27 |website=Green Shinto |language=en-GB}}</ref><ref name="Picken-2010" />{{Rp|page=6}}
== History == The exact year of foundation for Tagata Shrine is unknown, but it is believed to be over 1500 years old. It is known for combining beliefs related to fertility and agriculture.<ref name="Picken-2010" />{{Rp|page=6}}
It is listed as a [[:en:Myojin Taisha|Myojin Taisha]] in the [[Engishiki Jinmyōchō]].
== Harvest festival == {{Main|Hōnensai}} {{Infobox holiday | holiday_name = Hōnensai | type = shinto | religious_affiliation = [[Shinto]] |image = Hōnen Matsuri 2.JPG | religious_affiliation = [[Shinto]] |imagesize = 250px | caption = Hōnensai at {{ill|Tagata Shrine|simple|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tagata Shrine|qq=}} in Komaki|official_name = | nickname = | observedby = Japan | litcolor = | longtype = Religious | significance = Celebrates the blessings of a bountiful harvest and all manner of prosperity and fertility | begins = | ends = | scheduling = same day each year | date = 15 March | celebrations = | observances = | relatedto =|qq=draft|qq=draft}}
[[File:Hōnen Matsuri 6.JPG|thumb|Hōnensai]]
{{Nihongo|Harvest Festival|豊年祭|Hōnensai}} is a [[:en:Fertility|Fertility]] [[:en:Festival|Festival]] celebrated every year on March 15 at the shrine.<ref name="e-periodica" /><ref name="Knapp-1997" /> ''Hōnen'' means ''prosperous year'' in Japanese, implying a rich harvest, while a ''[[Japanese festivals|Matsuri]]'' is a festival. The Hōnen festival and ceremony celebrate the blessings of a bountiful harvest and all manner of prosperity and fertility. [[File:Tagata Jinja (entrance).png|thumb|Tagata Jinja (田縣神社) in Komaki, Tagata, [[:en:Aichi Prefecture|Aichi Prefecture]] ]] The venerated Shinto deities are Mitoshi (御歳神, Mitoshi-no-kami) and female deity Tamahime (玉姫命, Tamahime-no-mikoto). Mitoshi is the son of the Shinto male deity [[Toshigami]] (年神) or known by local as Ōtoshi (大歳神, Ōtoshi-no-kami) and grandson of the Shinto deity [[Susanoo-no-Mikoto|Susanoo]]. Tamahime is a princess and the daughter of Ō'arata (大荒田命, Ō'arata-no-Mikoto), the matriarch of [[Owari clan|''Owari'' clan]] (尾張氏) of her husband {{ill|Takeinadane|ja|建稲種命|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Takeinadane|qq=}} (健稲種命, Take'inadane-no-mikoto) who were blessed with two sons and four daughters. After her husband's death, she returned to his hometown Arata (situated close to Komaki), encouraged to cultivate with the help of her father Ō'arata, honor and achieved his achievements.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Small village gets real big at ancient celebration |url=https://www.mcasiwakuni.marines.mil/Iwakuni-News/News-Stories/News-Article-Display/Article/506486/small-village-gets-real-big-at-ancient-celebration/https%3A%2F%2Fwww.mcasiwakuni.marines.mil%2FIwakuni-News%2FNews-Stories%2FNews-Article-Display%2FArticle%2F506486%2Fsmall-village-gets-real-big-at-ancient-celebration%2F |access-date=2023-11-18 |website=Marine Corps Air Station Iwakuni, Japan |language=en-US}}</ref>
[[File:Youbutsu (O-owasegata).png|thumb|the shrine of the ''Youbutsu'' (陽物, lit. "the male object") or ''ō-owase-gata'' (大男茎形, lit. "the grand Phallus shape/ object") ]]
In [[:en:Inuyama, Aichi|Inuyama City]], there is another festival Sunday before at [[Ōagata Shrine]] (大縣神社). This festival includes floats shaped like a [[:en:Vulva|Vulva]], which complement the phallic-shaped mikoshi used in the festival.<ref name="D-2012" />
