{{afc comment|Wikidata entry [[d:Q60581]] Wikidata name: Tagata Shrine [[User:Immanuelle|Immanuelle]] ([[User talk:Immanuelle|talk]]) 09:41, 11 June 2025 (UTC)}} {{Short description|Shinto shrine}}
{{Infobox religious building| religious_affiliation = [[Shinto]]|religious_affiliation = [[Shinto]]|religious_affiliation = [[Shinto]]|religious_affiliation = [[Shinto]]| religious_affiliation = [[Shinto]] | religious_affiliation = Shinto | religious_affiliation = [[Shinto]] |image = File:Tagata jinja haiden 2020-12 ac (1).jpg | deity = {{ill|Toshigami|qid=Q3028663}} | location = {{ill|Komaki|qid=Q389537}} | coordinates = {{Coord|35.31583333|N|136.94111111|E|region:JP_type:landmark|display=inline,title}} }} '''Tagata Shrine''' (田縣神社) is a small shrine located in [[:en:Komaki|Komaki]] City, [[:en:Aichi Prefecture|Aichi Prefecture]], Japan, near [[Nagoya Airfield]].<ref name="Picken-2010">{{Cite book |last=Picken |first=Stuart D. B. |url=https://www.amazon.ca/Historical-Dictionary-Dictionaries-Religions-Philosophies-ebook/dp/B004MYFMR6/ref=sr_1_1?keywords=9780810873728&linkCode=qs&qid=1700275947&s=books&sr=1-1 |title=Historical Dictionary of Shinto |date=2010-12-28 |publisher=Scarecrow Press |edition=2 |language=English}}</ref>{{Rp|page=6}}
Tagata Shrine is famous for its Harvest Festival [[Hōnensai]], or the penis festival held annually on March 15.<ref name="e-periodica" /><ref name="Knapp-1997">{{Cite book |last=Knapp |first=Bettina L. |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5isFdtMGwVwC&dq=tagata+shrine&pg=PA246 |title=Women in Myth |date=1997-01-01 |publisher=SUNY Press |isbn=978-0-7914-3164-1 |language=en}}</ref> The festival has received large amounts of attention.<ref name="e-periodica">https://www.e-periodica.ch/cntmng?pid=act-001%3A1959%3A16%3A%3A995</ref>
It is near [[Ōagata Shrine]] which has a similar yonic festival the Sunday before this festival.<ref name="D-2012">{{Cite web |last=D |first=John |date=2012-03-24 |title=Fertility festival (Oh-agata/ Oagata Jinja) |url=https://www.greenshinto.com/2012/03/24/hime-no-miya-festival-ogata-jinja/ |access-date=2023-04-27 |website=Green Shinto |language=en-GB}}</ref><ref name="Picken-2010" />{{Rp|page=6}}
== History == The exact year of foundation for Tagata Shrine is unknown, but it is believed to be over 1500 years old. It is known for combining beliefs related to fertility and agriculture.<ref name="Picken-2010" />{{Rp|page=6}}
It is listed as a [[:en:Myojin Taisha|Myojin Taisha]] in the [[Engishiki Jinmyōchō]].
